I found this website today: https://dnsdumpster.com/
It allows you to search for hostnames that end with a particular domain name.  This is very handy for digging further than the surface of just the main www IP address.

>>203ff837-ad6d-4a90-9e29-579ed5b0ce79
one final point of clarification: zeronet is peer to peer.  This means you communicate directly with other users in the zeronet network rather than through a central server in traditional website hosting.
Because this is peer-to-peer, this means any peer can see the IP addresses of other peers within the network.   The window full of dates and IP addresses is a realtime live feed of IP addresses that my zeronet is communicating with.  Posting or loading content reveals your IP address to other peers.   Some of those peers, are apparently spying on us.

>>4ae602d0-4c94-4773-ad8e-126ea94680bc
If you run the hardware you can pull packets from the network connection and see all the IPs that you're communicating with.  Start by learning about 'pcap', the underlying packet capture technology.
The baseline tool for packet capture is tcpdump.  There's a version for windows users called windump.   There are also fancy GUI ones like wireshark or libraries you can use to do this programmatically.
Or if you're running the python client on the command line, you can see the IPs right in the console output.

>>646c95a2-0c96-441d-b912-ad7f318ae0a6
I suspect that it's a matter of cache.  domaintools caches their answer for a while.  Eventually they'll see the new answer.
Currently epik has 8ch's DNS locked up tight.  Epik are the authoritative nameservers for 8ch.   They have configured their DNS servers to be authoritative for 8ch, but they have removed all DNS records.  Effectively making it so that 8ch.net doesn't resolve to any IP address.  To me, it kind of seems like epik is holding 8ch down.
EDIT: yeah, I was wrong.  epik is trying to help, not hold them down.  See >>dd0fb18a-5033-4acc-b0d2-bebcc155758e
